<p><strong><p><strong>Western Rattlesnake (<em>Crotalus oreganus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Viperidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Crotalus oreganus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Western Rattlesnake<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Western Rattlesnake has a length of 15-65 inches. It is a blotched rattlesnake, usually with a light stripe extending from behind the eye to the corner of the mouth. The blotches are various shades of brown to black, and are usually edged with a darker color and often with light-colored borders. Ground color of this snake varies greatly over its wide range; colors may be cream, yellowish, gray, pink, greenish, brown, or black. The tail has dark and light rings, but they do not usually contrast sharply with body color. It is the only rattlesnake that usually has more than 2 internasals touching the rostral. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/identification/snakesid/crotalusviridis.id.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This rattlesnake resides in a great variety of habitats such as shrub-covered coastal sand dunes to timberline and from prairies and desert-edge habitats of mesquite scrublands to piñon-juniper woodland and montane forests. It prefers rocky outcrops, talus slopes, rocky stream courses, and ledges. Females bear 1-25 young between August-October. It eats mammals, birds, lizards, snakes, amphibians, and insects. This snake is venomous and potentially dangerous!</p>
